WEBVTT

00:07.684 --> 00:09.884
Thank you.

00:11.120 --> 00:14.489
You've got the police chief of
Rome and his people at 3:30.

00:14.491 --> 00:16.958
Make sure the espresso machine
is up and running.

00:16.960 --> 00:19.260
Good. Done.

00:19.262 --> 00:20.428
Pretty much.

00:20.430 --> 00:21.562
Let's have it.
Believe me,

00:21.564 --> 00:22.597
you don't want it.

00:22.599 --> 00:24.165
A group called
“Battle for Peace”

00:24.167 --> 00:25.600
is applying for a permit

00:25.602 --> 00:28.169
to demonstrate
at Veterans Memorial Plaza.

00:28.171 --> 00:29.804
Battle for Peace
is an oxymoron.

00:29.806 --> 00:31.439
Emphasis on “moron.”

00:31.441 --> 00:32.874
That goes to Community Affairs.

00:32.876 --> 00:35.309
It did. From the lieutenant

00:35.311 --> 00:37.311
to the captain,
to the C.O.,

00:37.313 --> 00:39.046
to the chief, to you.

00:39.048 --> 00:41.249
Demonstrations are being held
every day in this city.

00:41.251 --> 00:43.818
Now can I please have my coffee
and read my paper?

00:43.820 --> 00:48.489
Not demonstrations that involve
burning an American flag.

00:51.060 --> 00:53.294
All right.

00:53.296 --> 00:55.396
They're led by a kid
named David Gore--

00:55.398 --> 00:57.398
young but smart, media-savvy.

00:57.400 --> 00:59.100
You want me to contact legal?

00:59.102 --> 01:00.701
Maybe there's a way out of this.

01:00.703 --> 01:04.272
Supreme Court says flag-burning
is protected speech.

01:04.274 --> 01:08.276
Having said that,
I want a sit-down

01:08.278 --> 01:11.012
with this media-savvy whiz kid.

01:11.014 --> 01:12.346
You sure that's a good idea?

01:12.348 --> 01:14.815
No, but set it up.

01:20.256 --> 01:23.024
So, thank you for letting us
come talk to you guys today.

01:23.026 --> 01:26.093
And remember, if you need help,
that's what we're here for.

01:26.095 --> 01:28.863
(applause)

01:30.199 --> 01:31.999
Now, Officers Reagan
and Janko have agreed

01:32.001 --> 01:33.801
to answer some questions?
Yeah.

01:34.637 --> 01:35.670
Rita.

01:35.672 --> 01:37.872
Do you ever worry
about getting hurt?

01:37.874 --> 01:40.575
That's a risk that you take when
you become a police officer.

01:40.577 --> 01:42.276
But we try to be careful.

01:42.278 --> 01:43.411
JAMIE:
We're trained to handle

01:43.413 --> 01:44.712
all types of
situations, and you rely

01:44.714 --> 01:46.881
on your partner
to watch your back.

01:46.883 --> 01:48.950
Officer Janko?

01:48.952 --> 01:51.819
Aren't you kind of hot to be a cop?
(laughter)

01:51.821 --> 01:53.287
Tommy, that's
inappropriate.

01:53.289 --> 01:56.123
That's the reason that I ride
with Officer Reagan.

01:56.125 --> 01:58.659
It kind of balances things out
a little bit.

01:58.661 --> 02:01.095
(laughter)

02:02.031 --> 02:03.064
Lily.

02:03.066 --> 02:04.599
You said it's the NYPD's job

02:04.601 --> 02:05.800
to help people?

02:05.802 --> 02:07.468
That's right.

02:07.470 --> 02:09.437
Well, a cop killed my father.

02:09.439 --> 02:10.770
He didn't do anything wrong,

02:10.773 --> 02:13.774
but they shot him anyway.

02:15.311 --> 02:17.478
Cops are murderers.

02:17.480 --> 02:19.880
(students murmuring quietly)

02:23.219 --> 02:25.620
Got it. We're on our way.

02:25.622 --> 02:28.089
Port Authority cop
just detained our guy.

02:28.091 --> 02:29.890
Told you he'd try
to skip town.

02:29.892 --> 02:31.892
Must be your lucky day.
Yup.

02:32.829 --> 02:33.995
Detective Reagan?

02:33.997 --> 02:36.330
Yeah?
Anthony Abetemarco.

02:36.332 --> 02:38.132
I'm an investigator
for the D.A.'s office.

02:38.134 --> 02:39.934
Oh. Congratulations.

02:39.936 --> 02:41.769
Whatever it is
will have to wait.

02:41.771 --> 02:43.804
Yeah, you worked
the Marcus Donovan homicide

02:43.806 --> 02:44.905
with Detective Darryl Reid?

02:44.907 --> 02:46.507
Yeah, about a hundred
years ago. Why?

02:46.509 --> 02:47.875
What's this all about?

02:47.877 --> 02:50.211
There's evidence of serious
procedural irregularities

02:50.213 --> 02:51.879
by the NYPD.

02:52.849 --> 02:56.017
Detective Reid's already
jammed up.

02:56.019 --> 02:58.219
Now we want to talk to you.

03:00.523 --> 03:02.957
Right this way.

03:03.760 --> 03:05.693
ANTHONY:
You know you're under

03:05.695 --> 03:07.595
no obligation to speak
to me, Detective.

03:07.597 --> 03:10.665
Well, I got
nothing to hide.

03:10.667 --> 03:13.901
What was your relationship
with Detective Reid?

03:13.903 --> 03:16.270
Well, we weren't dating,
if that's what you mean.

03:16.272 --> 03:17.838
You think this is a joke?
Yeah, I do

03:17.840 --> 03:20.141
think it's a joke. In fact,
I think it's a bunch of crap.

03:20.143 --> 03:21.809
All right? I worked
with the guy

03:21.811 --> 03:23.377
for eight months seven years
ago. He was a good cop.

03:23.379 --> 03:24.445
Yeah, well, we have reason

03:24.447 --> 03:26.113
to believe
he planted blood evidence

03:26.115 --> 03:27.481
on the clothing

03:27.483 --> 03:29.417
of Marcus Donovan,
which led to his conviction.

03:29.419 --> 03:31.285
What led to his conviction
was the fact

03:31.287 --> 03:32.687
that he killed an elderly couple

03:32.689 --> 03:34.522
after they cashed
their Social Security check.

03:34.524 --> 03:35.956
There were no witnesses.

03:35.958 --> 03:37.892
The gun was never recovered.

03:37.894 --> 03:39.326
There's no witnesses

03:39.328 --> 03:41.762
because everybody's scared
to death of Marcus Donovan

03:41.764 --> 03:44.398
'cause he's a maniac.
The fact remains that Donovan was convicted

03:44.400 --> 03:46.934
because the victims' blood
was found on his shirt,

03:46.936 --> 03:48.769
and Reid put it there.

03:48.771 --> 03:50.271
The question is,

03:50.273 --> 03:52.006
did you know about it?

03:52.008 --> 03:53.908
You're joking, right?

03:53.910 --> 03:56.277
If you were part of this
in any way, Detective,

03:56.279 --> 03:57.745
now's the time to come clean.

03:57.747 --> 04:00.147
I mean, come on,
I ask that question of perps

04:00.149 --> 04:01.949
every single day myself,
all right?

04:03.119 --> 04:04.819
(knocking)

04:04.821 --> 04:06.587
We got a
time-sensitive matter

04:06.589 --> 04:08.255
related to an ongoing
investigation.

04:08.257 --> 04:09.990
What do you know? Got to go.

04:09.992 --> 04:11.692
I got more questions,
Detective.

04:11.694 --> 04:13.260
Have fun with that.

04:13.262 --> 04:15.229
What is he talking about
in there?

04:15.231 --> 04:17.130
Nothing. Bunch of hot air.

04:17.132 --> 04:20.166
You think they're trying to get
you to hang Reid out to dry?

04:20.168 --> 04:21.869
Reid is a good cop, okay?

04:21.870 --> 04:24.405
He would never have to plant
evidence to make a case,

04:24.407 --> 04:27.108
especially against a
rat like Marcus Donovan.

04:27.110 --> 04:28.809
Sounds like
they got him pretty good.

04:28.811 --> 04:30.444
Come on. He's a
decorated detective.

04:30.446 --> 04:32.480
Marcus Donovan's got
a rap sheet a mile long.

04:32.482 --> 04:35.282
Who would you believe? And
why'd you pull me out of there?

04:35.284 --> 04:36.650
What's so pressing?

04:38.721 --> 04:40.888
Close the door.

04:43.860 --> 04:46.093
What are you doing here?

04:46.095 --> 04:49.997
Violating about a dozen rules
of protocol, but we got to talk.

04:49.999 --> 04:53.067
Does this have anything to do
with, uh, your crony over here

04:53.069 --> 04:55.770
asking me questions about
a case from seven years ago?

04:55.772 --> 04:57.671
Yeah, and you didn't
hear it from me,

04:57.673 --> 05:00.341
but don't say another word
without an attorney present.

05:00.343 --> 05:02.109
Why the hell
do I need a lawyer?

05:02.111 --> 05:05.246
We've been investigating
Darryl Reid for two months.

05:05.248 --> 05:07.114
We have him dead
to rights on perjury

05:07.116 --> 05:08.816
and tampering
with physical evidence.

05:08.818 --> 05:10.951
I don't believe it.

05:10.953 --> 05:12.653
Yeah, well, you better.

05:13.923 --> 05:15.489
His career is in
serious jeopardy,

05:15.491 --> 05:17.057
and he's probably going to jail.

05:17.059 --> 05:21.128
And anyone complicit in
those crimes is going down, too.

